</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 World Sales of New Securities Surged 29% in 1993: Sales climbed to a record 
$1.47 trillion, enriching Wall Street in the process. The lowest U.S. bond 
yields in 30 years, record stock prices and booming investor demand sparked the 
increase from 1992's $1.14 trillion, the previous record, according to 
information compiled by Securities Data Co.Last year was "a great year for Wall 
Street," said New York Stock Exchange Chairman William Donaldson. "An explosive 
growth in mutual funds," caused by investors seeking higher returns, drove 
securities higher, he said. Wall Street is not looking for a repeat in 1994. 
Companies that sold bonds last year to refinance older ones with higher 
interest coupons are unlikely to issue as much debt in the year ahead. 
</P>
